Wash and dry all produce. Bring @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit} and @water{1%cup} to a boil in a #medium pot{}. Core and seed @red bell pepper{1}(cored and seeded), then thinly slice. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Trim @scallions{2}(trimmed), then separate whites from greens. Thinly slice whites. Finely mince greens. Zest @lemon{1} until you have ½ tsp zest, then cut into halves.

Once liquid is boiling, add @Israeli couscous{1/2%cup} to #pot{}. Cook, uncovered, until al dente, ~{10-11%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper and cook, tossing, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add scallion whites and garlic to pan. Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute} longer. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and set aside.

Pat @sirloin steak{12%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{}. Season all over with @cumin{1%tsp}, salt, and pepper. Heat another drizzle of @vegetable oil{3%tsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add steak and cook to desired doneness, ~{4-7%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and set aside to rest.

Add veggie mixture, @spinach{5%ounce}, lemon zest, and a drizzle of oil to pot with couscous. Season to taste with salt and pepper. In a #small bowl{}, mix scallion greens, a large drizzle of oil, and a squeeze of lemon juice. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Thinly slice steak against the grain. Divide couscous salad between plates. Top with steak and scallion dressing.

> Cumin is one of our favorite spices to cook with because it has tons of deep, earthy flavor without any heat. Its effect is subtle yet unmistakable, elevating steak to new heights in this recipe. It also loves a good contrast: here, it embraces a pucker-y scallion dressing with lemon and the veggie flavors of spinach and red pepper tossed with couscous.